1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,130
The most important person present is the one person most active in introducing himself.

2
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:10,770
It's always a big person who walks up to you, offers his hand,

3
00:00:10,770 --> 00:00:16,770
and says, Hello, I'm Jack R. Digest this observation for a moment,

4
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:22,610
and you'll discover the reason the fellow is important is that he works at building friendships.

5
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:25,169
Think right toward people.

6
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:29,730
As a friend of mine expresses it, I may not be very important to him,

7
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:31,490
but he's important to me.

8
00:00:31,680 --> 00:00:34,289
That's why I've got to get to know him.

9
00:00:34,880 --> 00:00:39,090
Have you ever noticed how people freeze while waiting for elevators?

10
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:45,569
Unless they are with someone they know, most folks never say anything to the person standing beside them.

11
00:00:45,920 --> 00:00:49,650
One day, I resolved to do a little experimenting.

12
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,449
I resolved to say something to the stranger who was waiting as I was.

13
00:00:54,720 --> 00:00:58,850
I kept track of his reaction 25 consecutive times.

14
00:00:59,040 --> 00:01:03,890
And 25 times, I got back a positive, friendly response.

15
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:11,010
Now, talking to strangers may not be very urbane, but most people like it nevertheless.

16
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:13,329
And here is the big payoff.

17
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:19,010
When you make a pleasant remark to a stranger, you make him feel one degree better.

18
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:22,049
This makes you feel better and helps you relax.

19
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:27,010
Every time you say something pleasant to another person, you compensate yourself.

20
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:30,850
It's like warming up your automobile on a cold morning.

21
00:01:32,560 --> 00:01:37,890
Here are six ways to win friends by exercising just a little initiative.

22
00:01:37,890 --> 00:01:38,770
1.

23
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:47,250
Introduce yourself to others at every possible opportunity, at parties, meetings, on airplanes, at work, everywhere.

24
00:01:47,250 --> 00:01:48,530
2.

25
00:01:49,040 --> 00:01:52,370
Be sure the other person gets your name straight.

26
00:01:52,370 --> 00:01:53,809
3.

27
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:59,010
Be sure you can pronounce the other person's name the way he pronounces it.

28
00:01:59,010 --> 00:02:01,250
4.

29
00:02:01,520 --> 00:02:06,689
Write down the other person's name and be mighty sure you have it spelled correctly.

30
00:02:06,880 --> 00:02:10,370
People have a fetish about the correct spelling of their own names.

31
00:02:10,480 --> 00:02:13,890
If possible, get his address and phone number also.

32
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:15,329
5.

33
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:21,250
Drop a personal note or make a phone call to the new friends you feel you want to know better.

34
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:23,329
This is an important point.

35
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:29,169
Most successful people follow through on new friends with a letter or a phone call.

36
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:35,329
Six, and last but not least, say pleasant things to strangers.

37
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:39,250
It warms you up and gets you ready for the task ahead.

38
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:45,329
Putting these six rules to work is really thinking right about people.

39
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:49,250
To be sure, it is not the way the average person thinks.

40
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:53,730
Mr. Average never takes the initiative in making introductions.

41
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:57,569
He waits for the other person to introduce himself first.

42
00:02:57,920 --> 00:02:59,330
Take the initiative.

43
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:01,169
Be like the successful.

44
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:03,250
Go out of your way to meet people.

45
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:04,770
And don't be timid.

46
00:03:04,770 --> 00:03:06,929
Don't be afraid to be unusual.

47
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:11,809
Find out who the other person is, and be sure he knows who you are.

48
00:03:14,080 --> 00:03:21,569
Recently, an associate and I were retained to do a preliminary screening of an applicant for an industrial sales job.

49
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:26,929
We found the applicant, whom we'll call Ted, to have some good qualifications.

50
00:03:27,120 --> 00:03:33,010
He was exceptionally intelligent, made a fine appearance, and seemed to have a lot of ambition.

51
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:38,929
But we found something that forced us to disqualify him, at least temporarily.

52
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:41,490
Ted's big limitation was this.

53
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:44,530
He expected perfection in other people.

54
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:51,569
Ted was annoyed by many little things, like mistakes in grammar, people who were messy with cigarettes,

55
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:54,929
people who had bad taste in clothes, and so on.

56
00:03:55,440 --> 00:04:02,049
Ted was surprised to learn this fact about himself, but he was eager to get into higher-paying work,

57
00:04:02,160 --> 00:04:07,490
and he asked whether there was anything we could tell him to help overcome his weakness.

